# Single-line simple expressions

## Rule

When a statement or JSX tag is simple enough to read on one line, keep it on one line. Do not introduce manual line breaks just because a formatter permits wrapping.

Prefer single-line formatting for:

- Short `const` / `let` / `var` initializers, including simple strings and one-call expressions.
- `useRef(false)` / `useState(() => value)` style hook initializers with short comments after the semicolon.
- Short function declarations, component parameter destructuring, and prop types.
- Simple ternaries where both branches are short.
- JSX tags whose props fit comfortably on one line.
- Single-line `if` guards with only `return` (see `inline-if-return.mdc`).

## Prefer

```typescript
const ASSISTANT_CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT = "You are a helpful assistant for the Ratatouille recipe app. …";
const commitFromKeyboardReference = useRef(false); /* Avoids firing `onCommit` twice when Enter triggers both keydown and blur */
const [formCommitted, setFormCommitted] = useState(() => isFormMode ? props.defaultValue ?? "" : "");
const hiddenFormValue = isFormMode ? (showInput ? draft : formCommitted) : null;
```

```tsx
export function RecipeListRowLink({ recipeId, title, thumbSrc }: RecipeListRowLinkProps) {
  return null;
}

<button type="button" className={previewZoneGrowSectionClassName} onClick={onUploadZoneClick}>
  <span className={previewZoneTitleClassName}>
    <IconUpload className={previewZoneIconClassName} aria-hidden />
  </span>
</button>

<label className={previewZoneGrowSectionClassName}>
  <span className={previewZoneTitleClassName}>
    <IconLink className={previewZoneIconClassName} aria-hidden />
  </span>
</label>
```

## Avoid

```typescript
const ASSISTANT_CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT =
  "You are a helpful assistant for the Ratatouille recipe app. …";

const commitFromKeyboardReference =
  useRef(
    false
  ); /* Avoids firing `onCommit` twice when Enter triggers both keydown and blur */

const [formCommitted, setFormCommitted] = useState(() =>
  isFormMode ? (props.defaultValue ?? "") : ""
);

const hiddenFormValue = isFormMode
  ? showInput
    ? draft
    : formCommitted
  : null;
```

```tsx
export function RecipeListRowLink({
  recipeId,
  title,
  thumbSrc,
}: RecipeListRowLinkProps) {
  return null;
}

<button
  type="button"
  className={previewZoneGrowSectionClassName}
  onClick={onUploadZoneClick}
>
```

## Exceptions

- Complex expressions, long object literals, long JSX prop lists, and multi-line JSX children can use normal multi-line formatting.
- Do not fight automated formatting for generated files. For hand-edited code, prefer a concise one-line form when it stays readable.
- If a line is genuinely too long to review comfortably, split at a meaningful boundary instead of splitting a trivial expression into many lines.

## Scope

Applies to **new and edited** code in matched files. When editing existing code, avoid churn outside the touched expressions.
